* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Arima Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} – Located in Kubo, Kaizuka City, Osaka Prefecture. A shrine associated with the Amaka clan, powerful families of the Amagawa Estate. It was founded in 507, very close in date to this shrine.
* {{ill|lt=Gyōgūdō|Q17225570|WD=Q17225570|1=Yukiai-dō Temple}} (Kamisuyachō) – When Shinto rites of the former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amagawa Estate|1=UNKNOWN}} were held, the lower districts (Gokurakuji, Hata, Nagaregi) and upper districts (Hatta, Kamisuya, Magami) would meet at this hall and then proceed together to worship at Yashirogi Shrine.
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Magami Hachidai Ryūō Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} (Magami-chō) – After an accident in which people collecting earth at the former site of Yasaka Shrine were buried and died, the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hachidai Ryūō|1=UNKNOWN}} and the {{ill|lt=Ujigami|Q1392097|WD=Q1392097|1=Ubusunagami}} were enshrined here after the war.
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kaigan-ji ruins|1=UNKNOWN}} (Handa-chō, Kaizuka City) – A temple built by Okabe Nobukatsu of the Kishiwada Domain to memorialize the Tokugawa family. Abolished in Meiji 2. The gravestone of the monk Ien Hōshi Daiku bears the inscription “Amagawa Ichinomiya (Yashirogi Shrine), 11th generation.”

